USE Social_Media;


/*
You are an expert SQL assistant.  
Before answering any question, refer strictly to the database schema provided below.  
All SQL queries, joins, and analyses must be based ONLY on this schema — table names, column names, and relationships mentioned here.  
Do not assume any extra tables or columns unless explicitly stated.  
If a question is ambiguous, clarify it using the schema context rather than inventing new fields.  
Once you understand the schema, wait for my analytical question and generate the most accurate SQL query for it.

Tables and Key Columns:
  1. users(user_id, username, join_date, country)
  2. posts(post_id, user_id, content, created_at)
  3. comments(comment_id, post_id, user_id, comment_text, created_at)
  4. likes(like_id, post_id, user_id, created_at)
  5. followers(follower_id, user_id, follower_user_id, follow_date)
  6. hashtags(hashtag_id, tag_name, category)
  7. post_hashtags(id, post_id, hashtag_id)

Relationships:
  • Each user can create multiple posts.
  • Each post can have multiple likes and comments.
  • Users can follow each other (self-join in followers table).
  • Posts can be tagged with multiple hashtags (many-to-many via post_hashtags).
*/

--   "Generate SQL to find top 10 active users combining posts and comments."
--   "Find trending hashtags used in more than 20 posts."
-- ==============================================================

SELECT
    u.user_id,
    u.username,
    COUNT(DISTINCT p.post_id) + COUNT(DISTINCT c.comment_id) AS total_activity
FROM users u
LEFT JOIN posts p
    ON u.user_id = p.user_id
LEFT JOIN comments c
    ON u.user_id = c.user_id
GROUP BY u.user_id, u.username
ORDER BY total_activity DESC
LIMIT 10;

SELECT
    h.hashtag_id,
    h.tag_name,
    COUNT(DISTINCT ph.post_id) AS post_count
FROM hashtags h
JOIN post_hashtags ph
    ON h.hashtag_id = ph.hashtag_id
GROUP BY h.hashtag_id, h.tag_name
HAVING COUNT(DISTINCT ph.post_id) > 20
ORDER BY post_count DESC;


-- ==============================================================
-- Q1. Most Active Users (Posts + Comments)
-- ==============================================================
-- Objective : Find top 10 users based on combined number of posts and comments.
-- Example GenAI Prompt :
--   "Write SQL to find top 10 active users combining posts and comments count."
-- Write your query below 👇
-- --------------------------------------------------------------
-- Your Code ...

SELECT
    u.user_id,
    u.username,
    COUNT(DISTINCT p.post_id) + COUNT(DISTINCT c.comment_id) AS total_activity
FROM users u
LEFT JOIN posts p
    ON u.user_id = p.user_id
LEFT JOIN comments c
    ON u.user_id = c.user_id
GROUP BY u.user_id, u.username
ORDER BY total_activity DESC
LIMIT 10;

-- Solution Summary -- 
/*Use the users table as the base.
Join with:
posts to count posts per user.
comments to count comments per user.
Calculate total activity as:
total posts + total comments
Use LEFT JOIN to include users who may have only posts or only comments.
Apply DISTINCT in counts to avoid overcounting due to joins.
Group by user and order by total activity in descending order.
Limit the result to the top 10 users.

Key Insight:
This query provides a holistic view of user engagement, capturing both content creation (posts) 
and participation (comments), which is more meaningful than measuring activity using a single metric.
Business Value:
Helps identify highly engaged users.
Useful for recognizing influencers, power users, or community leaders.
Can guide reward systems or targeted engagement strategies.
This solution strictly follows the given schema and accurately answers the analytical requirement.
*/


-- ==============================================================
-- Q2. Most Liked Posts and Creators
-- ==============================================================
-- Objective : Identify posts with maximum likes along with their creator.
-- Example GenAI Prompt :
--   "Show top 10 posts with most likes and username."
-- --------------------------------------------------------------
-- Your Code ...
SELECT
    p.post_id,
    u.username,
    COUNT(l.like_id) AS total_likes
FROM posts p
JOIN users u
    ON p.user_id = u.user_id
LEFT JOIN likes l
    ON p.post_id = l.post_id
GROUP BY p.post_id, u.username
ORDER BY total_likes DESC
LIMIT 10;

-- Solution Summary -- 
/*Approach (Schema-Based)
Use the posts table as the base to identify each post.
Join users to retrieve the username of the user who created each post.
Left join likes to count how many likes each post has received.
Aggregate likes per post using COUNT.
Sort the results in descending order of total likes.
Limit the output to the top 10 posts.
Key Metric
Total Likes per Post = number of records in the likes table associated with a given post_id.
Outcome
The result displays the most liked posts on the platform, showing:
Each post’s identifier
The username of the post owner
*/


-- ==============================================================
-- Q3. Top Countries by Average Engagement
-- ==============================================================
-- Objective : Find countries with the highest average likes per post.
-- Example GenAI Prompt :
--   "Which countries have highest average likes per post?"
-- --------------------------------------------------------------
-- Your Code ...

SELECT
    u.country,
    AVG(COUNT(l.like_id)) OVER (PARTITION BY u.country) AS avg_likes_per_post
FROM users u
JOIN posts p
    ON u.user_id = p.user_id
LEFT JOIN likes l
    ON p.post_id = l.post_id
GROUP BY u.country, p.post_id
ORDER BY avg_likes_per_post DESC;


-- Solution Summary -- 
/*Approach (Schema-Based)
Join users → posts to associate posts with user countries.
Left join likes to count how many likes each post receives.
Aggregate likes per post, then compute the average likes per post per country.
Order results by the average in descending order to identify top countries.
Key Metric
Average Likes per Post per Country
= (Total likes on posts from a country) ÷ (Total posts from that country)
Outcome
The result highlights countries where posts tend to receive higher engagement on average, 
regardless of how many users or total posts exist in that country.*/



-- ==============================================================
-- Q4. Trending Hashtags (Used in >20 Posts)
-- ==============================================================
-- Objective : Find hashtags that appear in more than 20 posts.
-- Example GenAI Prompt :
--   "Find hashtags used in more than 20 posts."
-- --------------------------------------------------------------
-- Your Code ...
SELECT
    h.hashtag_id,
    h.tag_name,
    COUNT(DISTINCT ph.post_id) AS post_count
FROM hashtags h
JOIN post_hashtags ph
    ON h.hashtag_id = ph.hashtag_id
GROUP BY h.hashtag_id, h.tag_name
HAVING COUNT(DISTINCT ph.post_id) > 20
ORDER BY post_count DESC;


-- Solution Summary -- 
/*Approach (Schema-Based
Use the post_hashtags table to connect posts with hashtags.
Join hashtags to obtain hashtag details such as tag_name.
Group the data by each hashtag.
Count the distinct posts associated with each hashtag.
Filter results to include only hashtags that appear in more than 20 posts.
Key Metric
Post Count per Hashtag
= number of distinct post_id values linked to a given hashtag_id.
Outcome
The result identifies frequently used (popular) hashtags, showing which tags are widely
           applied across posts rather than repeatedly used on the same post
*/

-- ==============================================================
-- Q5. Top Influencers (Users with Most Followers)
-- ==============================================================
-- Objective : List users with the highest follower count.
-- Example GenAI Prompt :
--   "Find users with maximum followers."
-- --------------------------------------------------------------
-- Your Code ...

SELECT
    u.user_id,
    u.username,
    COUNT(f.follower_user_id) AS follower_count
FROM users u
JOIN followers f
    ON u.user_id = f.user_id
GROUP BY u.user_id, u.username
ORDER BY follower_count DESC;


-- Solution Summary -- 
/*Approach (Schema-Based)
Use the followers table to identify follow relationships.
user_id → the user being followed
follower_user_id → the user who follows
Group the data by user_id to count how many followers each user has.
Join with the users table to retrieve usernames.
Compare follower counts to identify users with the maximum number of followers.
Key Metric
Follower Count per User
= number of records in the followers table where user_id is followed.
Outcome
The result highlights the most-followed user(s) on the platform, showing:
User identity (via username)
Their total number of followers
*/


-- ==============================================================
-- Q6. Followers Who Never Interacted
-- ==============================================================
-- Objective : Identify users who follow others but have never liked or commented.
-- Example GenAI Prompt :
--   "Show users who follow others but never interacted."
-- --------------------------------------------------------------
-- Your Code ...
SELECT DISTINCT
    u.user_id,
    u.username
FROM users u
JOIN followers f
    ON u.user_id = f.follower_user_id
LEFT JOIN posts p
    ON u.user_id = p.user_id
LEFT JOIN comments c
    ON u.user_id = c.user_id
LEFT JOIN likes l
    ON u.user_id = l.user_id
WHERE p.post_id IS NULL
  AND c.comment_id IS NULL
  AND l.like_id IS NULL;


-- Solution Summary -- 
/*Approach (Schema-Based)
Use the followers table to find users who follow at least one other user
(follower_user_id).
Treat these users as the candidate set.
Check for absence of interaction by ensuring the user:
Has no records in posts
Has no records in comments
Has no records in likes
Join with the users table to retrieve user details.
Key Definition
Never interacted = user has not posted, not commented, and not liked any post.
Outcome
The result returns users who are socially connected (they follow others) 
         but are passive in terms of content engagement, meaning they do not create or interact with posts.
*/


-- ==============================================================
-- Q7. Hashtags with Highest Engagement
-- ==============================================================
-- Objective : Calculate total engagement (likes + comments) for each hashtag.
-- Example GenAI Prompt :
--   "Calculate engagement score per hashtag."
-- --------------------------------------------------------------
-- Your Code ...
SELECT
    h.hashtag_id,
    h.tag_name,
    COUNT(DISTINCT l.like_id) + COUNT(DISTINCT c.comment_id) AS engagement_score
FROM hashtags h
JOIN post_hashtags ph
    ON h.hashtag_id = ph.hashtag_id
JOIN posts p
    ON ph.post_id = p.post_id
LEFT JOIN likes l
    ON p.post_id = l.post_id
LEFT JOIN comments c
    ON p.post_id = c.post_id
GROUP BY h.hashtag_id, h.tag_name
ORDER BY engagement_score DESC;

-- Solution Summary -- 
/*Approach (Schema-Based)
Use post_hashtags to link hashtags with posts.
Join hashtags to identify each hashtag.
Join posts to reach post-level interactions.
Left join likes and comments to count interactions on those posts.
Aggregate likes and comments per hashtag.
Combine these counts to form an overall engagement score.
Key Metric
Engagement Score per Hashtag
= (Total likes on posts using the hashtag) + (Total comments on posts using the hashtag)
Outcome
The result ranks hashtags by how much user interaction their associated posts generate, 
      rather than just how frequently they are used.
*/


-- ==============================================================
-- Q8. Busiest Posting Hours or Days
-- ==============================================================
-- Objective : Find which hour/day sees most posting activity.
-- Example GenAI Prompt :
--   "Write SQL to show which hour or weekday sees most posts."
-- --------------------------------------------------------------
-- Your Code ...
SELECT
    EXTRACT(HOUR FROM created_at) AS post_hour,
    COUNT(*) AS post_count
FROM posts
GROUP BY post_hour
ORDER BY post_count DESC;

-- Solution Summary -- 
/*Approach (Schema-Based)
Use the posts table as the source of post creation data.
Extract the hour and weekday from the created_at timestamp.
Group posts by hour and by weekday separately.
Count the number of posts in each group.
Compare counts to identify the hour and/or weekday with the highest posting activity.
Key Metrics
Posts per Hour = number of posts created in each hour of the day.
Posts per Weekday = number of posts created on each day of the week.
Outcome
The analysis reveals:
The peak posting hour, indicating when users are most active during the day.
The most active weekday, showing which day has the highest content creation.
*/


